@popaganda. I've thought about this a lot lately - the idea that things outside myself happening randomly might result in something beautiful, non-2nd-law, that there's a future for my kids. Been struggling with the death of a very close friend for the last 6 months, and I (for some reason, I'm not going to defend or explain it) started reading the works of Rene Gerard, the mimetic desire philosopher ("Man is the creature who does not know what to desire, and he turns to others in order to make up his mind" etc.) Previously I had read more stoic philosophy and resonated with that. Historically I come from a Christian perspective, though never bought into evangelicalism even as a kid.

So, something very bad happened, and it rocked me harder than anything has in a long time. Spoke at my friend's memorial, told part of his life story, and wept with hundreds of people. Didn't end for me there, though. Became very... depressed is probably the wrong term. Nihilistic is closer, but also wrong. Maybe just "not hopeful".

Don't really have a logical conclusion for this, like I usually try to have, except to say: I still believe in beautiful things, people, experiences. Coffee while my kids chat with me in the morning. Sitting on the porch watching the sun rise earlier. And I do believe that all manner of things will be well in the end, and I choose to relax that tense knot inside myself, and I choose to move forward, and grow or decline, and move forward with as much grace as I can muster. I don't surf, and I find the overuse of the analogy annoying, but yes, to surf through the ups and downs instead of trying to master the waves.

What I found interesting and applicable here;

1) When watching a reel/youtube/reading a blog ask yourself is this learning or entertainment? Both are fine, just be honest with yourself

2) Many people are trapped in a "First I must learn all the things, *then* I will make something" and Karpathy points to the power of striving to make something as the engine of learning, *needing* to know to get your thing into reality is much more motivating than just filling in squares on some educational bingo card

